  "why": "CureFuzz enforces naturalness of mutated inputs (e.g., small perturbations, legality checks, and discarding illegal/initial-crash states) but does not enforce semantic consistency requirements (not applicable here because the oracle detects crashes as new scenario outcomes rather than assuming semantic equivalence) nor does it bound cumulative distortion relative to the original seed across many iterations. Mutation is performed as small, stepwise perturbations to the currently selected seed and promising mutants are added back into the corpus for further mutation, which constrains plausibility only between successive steps rather than preventing gradual drift from the original seed.",
  "evidence": "Page 6, Section 3.4 (Seed Mutation / Seed Evaluation): \"Seed Mutation: Once a seed is selected from the corpus, the SeedMutation function generates a new mutated state by applying a small random perturbation to a selected state.\"; \"We need to ensure that the mutated seed lies in the legitimate state spaces , and the mutated seed would not trigger an initial crash. In our experiments, we have carefully addressed this concern and verified the validity of each mutated seed, details are given in Section 4.\". Page 6, Algorithm 2 (workflow showing iterative mutation and corpus addition): \"s <- SeedSelection(I); sδ <- SeedMutation(s); ... if isCrashed(s'δ) then C <- C ∪ s'δ; else if isInteresting(s'δ) then I <- I ∪ s'δ;\" (shows mutants are added back and can be reselected). Page 7, Section 4.2 (Environment-specific validity checks): \"When CureFuzz mutates a given state, small perturbations are randomly generated and added to the positions and angles of these vehicles. We use the CARLA simulator itself to check for the validity of the mutated state. All illegally mutated states and the states that trigger initial collision are discarded in our experiments.\" (Autonomous Driving); similar statements for ACAS Xu and BipedalWalker: \"states that fall outside legal space are automatically discarded.\" / \"illegal states can be easily detected and discarded.\". Nowhere does the paper describe enforcing semantic-equivalence constraints or controlling perturbation magnitude relative to the original seed across multiple iterations (i.e., no mechanism to prevent cumulative drift is described)."
